I’d send seven of my servants to go get him.
While I waited, I’d frown impatiently, and perhaps wind my watch, or play with my—with some expensive piece of jewelry I happen to be wearing.
Toby would approach me.
He’d bow to me—     I reach out my hand to him like this, giving him a stern look instead of my usual friendly smile—   And I’d say to him, “Cousin Toby, since I’ve been lucky enough to marry your niece, I have the right to say a few things to you—”   “You must stop being such a drunk.”     “And you’re wasting your time with that foolish knight—”   “That Sir Andrew—”
